\subsection{Strong Approximation}

\section{From Modular forms to Automorphic Forms}
Let $\Gamma = \Gamma_0(N)$ be the congruence subgroup of $\SL_2(\Z)$ consisting of matrices which are upper triangular modulo $N$. Corresponding to $\Gamma$, there is a compact open subgroup of $K_0(N)$ of $\SL_2(\A)$. Indeed, for $p$ a rational prime, consider the subgroup \[K_0(N)_p = \left \{
  \begin{pmatrix}
    a & b \\ c & d
  \end{pmatrix} \in \SL_2(\Z_p) : c \equiv 0 \bmod p^{v_p(N)}
  \right \},\]
where $v_p(N)$ denotes the maximum power of $p$ dividing $N$. When $p$ does not divide $N$, $K_0(N)_p$ is the maximal compact subgroup $\SL_2(\Z_p)$ of $\SL_2(\Q_p)$. Then define \[K_0(N) = \prod_p K_0(N)_p = \left \{
  \begin{pmatrix}
    a & b \\ c & d
  \end{pmatrix} \in \SL_2(\widehat \Z) : c \equiv 0 \bmod N
  \right \}\] 
Let $K_\infty$ be the maximal compact $SO_2$ of $SL_2(\R)$. Let $K = K_0(N)K_\infty$, so $K$ is a compact open subgroup of $\SL_2(\A)$. One recovers $\Gamma_0(N)$ from $K$ by $K_0(N) \cap \SL_2(\Q) = \Gamma_0(N)$. \\

Let $f$ be a modular form of weight $k$ with level $\Gamma$. For $\gamma \in \SL_2(\R)$, define the slash operator on $f$ by \[f|\gamma(z) = j(\gamma,z)^{-k}f(\gamma(z)).\] Here $j$ denotes the automorphy factor (which satsifies the cocycle condition). One can define a function $\varphi_f: \SL_2(\R) \to \C$ by \[\varphi_f(\gamma) = f|_\gamma(i).\]

Observe that this function is $\Gamma_0(N)$ invariant, so $\varphi_f: \Gamma_0(N)\backslash \SL_2(\R) \to \C$. But by strong approximation, \[\Gamma_0\backslash \SL_2(\R) \simeq \SL_2(\Q) \backslash \SL_2(\A) /K_0(N).\] Therefore, $\varphi_f$ is a function on the adelic quotient $\SL_2(\Q)\backslash \SL_2(\A)$ which is invariant under the compact set $K_0(N)$. \\

Furthermore, one checks that $K_\infty$ acts on $f$ through the slash operator by rotations. In other words, $\varphi_f$ is an eigenvector under the action of $K_\infty$ on $\SL_2(\R)$. \\

Since $f$ is holomorphic, $\Delta f = 0$ where $\Delta$ is the hyperbolic laplacian. Therefore $\varphi_f$ is an eigenvector of the action of $\mathcal Z_\g$ on $\SL_2(\R)$. This gives $\mathcal Z_\g$-finiteness of $\varphi_f$.

Check some growth conditions to make sure it is indeed an automorphic form. This comes from $f$ having moderate growth due to holomorphy at the cusps.

